    # BRCA1: Expert Analysis
    ## Biological Function
    BRCA1 is the central scaffolding hub of homologous recombination (HR) repair of DNA double-strand breaks. The 1863-aa protein integrates three functional modules: an N-terminal RING domain that heterodimerizes with BARD1 to form an E3 ubiquitin ligase, a central region harboring coiled-coil and DNA-binding activity that nucleates the BRCA1-PALB2-BRCA2-RAD51 axis driving strand invasion, and tandem C-terminal BRCT domains that read phospho-SXXF motifs on Abraxas, BACH1/FANCJ, and CtIP to assemble the A, B, and C complexes governing checkpoint signaling, fork protection, and end resection. The locus is large (~126 kb) and produces 33 protein-coding isoforms, with BRCA1-Δ11q being the most clinically relevant splice variant — it lacks most of exon 11 and confers partial PARP-inhibitor resistance in tumors that retain it. The moderate GC content (44.1%) and presence of Alu-rich introns explain BRCA1's well-documented susceptibility to large genomic rearrangements via non-allelic homologous recombination.
    ## Key Variants and Mutational Landscape
    Pathogenic variation is dominated by truncating frameshift and nonsense alleles distributed across the coding sequence, with two Ashkenazi Jewish founder mutations — c.68_69delAG (185delAG) and c.5266dupC (5382insC) — accounting for the majority of hereditary breast/ovarian cancer in that population. Missense variants are pathogenic almost exclusively when they disrupt the RING (e.g., C61G, which abolishes BARD1 binding and ligase activity) or BRCT folds (e.g., M1775R, R1699W), where saturation genome-editing data from Findlay et al. now provide functional scores for nearly every possible SNV. Large genomic rearrangements (BRCA1 exon 13 duplication, exon 8–13 deletions) constitute ~10% of pathogenic alleles and are missed by short-read sequencing without MLPA or CNV-aware pipelines. Promoter hypermethylation is the dominant somatic inactivation mechanism in sporadic basal-like breast and high-grade serous ovarian cancers and produces an HR-deficient phenotype phenocopying germline loss.
    ## Disease Associations
    Heterozygous loss-of-function carriers face cumulative lifetime risks of ~65–72% for breast cancer and ~40–45% for ovarian cancer, with elevated risks of fallopian tube, peritoneal, pancreatic, and male breast cancer; prostate cancer risk is more modest than for BRCA2. Tumors are characteristically basal-like, triple-negative, high-grade, and exhibit COSMIC SBS3 and ID6 mutational signatures plus HRD-LOH/TAI/LST genomic scars detectable by Myriad myChoice or equivalent assays. This HR deficiency is therapeutically actionable: PARP inhibitors (olaparib, niraparib, rucaparib, talazoparib) are FDA-approved across breast, ovarian, pancreatic, and prostate indications, and platinum sensitivity is a robust class effect. Resistance mechanisms — reversion mutations restoring the open reading frame, 53BP1/REV7/Shieldin loss, and BRCA1-Δ11q upregulation — are now standard interrogation targets in progressing patients.
    ## Experimental Recommendations
    For variant interpretation, anchor classifications in the Findlay SGE functional dataset and the ENIGMA consortium curated database before applying ACMG criteria; for novel VUS, run a HDR-GFP or DR-GFP reporter assay in BRCA1-null HCC1937 or U2OS-derived lines, complemented by RAD51 foci formation after ionizing radiation as an orthogonal HR readout. For tumor profiling, pair targeted sequencing with an HRD genomic-scar assay and BRCA1 promoter methylation calling — mutation status alone misses ~30% of HR-deficient tumors. For mechanistic work, isogenic BRCA1-knockout RPE1 or MCF10A lines reconstituted with variant cDNAs remain the cleanest system; for in vivo studies, the conditional Brca1^fl/fl;K14-Cre or Brg1-driven models recapitulate basal-like mammary tumorigenesis. Given the gene's size and rearrangement burden, any clinical-grade pipeline must include long-read or MLPA-based CNV detection — short-read SNV calling alone is insufficient.

